  "prompt": "How often should employees get a performance review?",
  "response": "The frequency of performance reviews can vary depending on the organization and its specific practices and culture. However, common intervals for performance reviews include:\n\n1. **Annually**: Many organizations conduct performance reviews once a year, typically at the end of the calendar or fiscal year.\n\n2. **Semi-annually**: Some organizations find it beneficial to conduct performance reviews twice a year. This can provide more opportunities for feedback and adjustments throughout the year.\n\n3. **Quarterly**: Conducting reviews every three months can help keep employees on track with short-term goals and allows for more frequent communication between employees and management.\n\n4. **Monthly**: In some high-paced or rapidly changing environments, monthly reviews can be useful. They allow for continuous feedback and quick pivots if needed.\n\n5. **Continuous Feedback**: While traditional reviews are useful, many organizations are moving towards continuous feedback systems. These allow managers and peers to provide ongoing feedback in real-time, rather than waiting for a formal review period.\n\nUltimately, the best approach depends on the company's culture, the nature of the work, and the goals of the performance review process. Regular check-ins and ongoing feedback are often more effective in maintaining employee engagement and development than relying solely on formal review periods.",
